In 2023, Has there been an increase or decrease in the overall number of cyber attacks compared to the previous periods? What sectors or industries were most targeted during this period?

¬According to the web sources I found, there has been an **increase** in the overall number of cyber attacks in 2023 compared to the previous periods. Cybersecurity statistics indicate that there are **2,200 cyber attacks per day**, with a cyber attack happening every **39 seconds** on average¹. The global volume of cyber attacks reached an **all-time high** in Q4 2022 with an average of **1168 weekly attacks per organization**², and rose by **7%** in Q1 2023 compared to the same period last year, with each firm facing an average of **1248 attacks per week**³. The global information security industry is forecasted to reach **$170.4 billion** by 2022¹.

The sectors or industries that were most targeted in 2023 are:

- **Education/Research**: This sector experienced the highest number of attacks, rising to an average of **2507 per organization per week** (a 15% increase compared to Q1 2022)³. Hackers exploited the rapid digitization and e-learning shift that academic institutions undertook in response to the COVID-19 pandemic³.
- **Government**: This sector experienced the second highest number of attacks, with an average of **1930 per organization per week** (a 41% increase compared to 2022)³. Hackers targeted government agencies and critical infrastructure for espionage, sabotage, or ransomware purposes³.
- **Healthcare**: This sector experienced the third highest number of attacks, with an average of **1815 per organization per week** (a 40% increase compared to 2022)³. Hackers targeted healthcare organisations for their valuable medical data, intellectual property, or ransomware payments³.

Other sectors that were also frequently attacked in 2023 include manufacturing, retail, finance, and technology³.

